const faq = [
  { q: `Why does Japanese have so many onomatopoeia?`, a: `Japanese culture values expressing subtle sensations and emotions precisely. Onomatopoeia fill gaps where regular adjectives and adverbs cannot capture the nuance. While English has maybe 200 commonly used sound words, Japanese has over 1,000+. They appear in everyday speech, not just manga and anime.` },
  { q: `Are onomatopoeia used in formal writing?`, a: `Giongo (actual sounds like ドンドン) appear occasionally in all contexts. Gitaigo (mimetic words like ふわふわ) are common in literature and advertising but generally avoided in academic or legal writing. In business, some are acceptable in casual emails but not formal documents.` },
  { q: `How can I learn onomatopoeia naturally?`, a: `Manga is the best resource — sound effects are written in katakana throughout every panel. Anime and variety shows use them constantly, especially in subtitles. Start by learning 20-30 common ones, then expand as you encounter new ones in context. Don't try to memorize all 1,000+ at once.` },
  { q: `What's the difference between giongo and gitaigo?`, a: `Giongo (擬音語) represents actual sounds you can hear: ドンドン (banging), ザーザー (heavy rain). Gitaigo (擬態語) represents states, feelings, or textures you can't actually hear: ふわふわ (fluffy), キラキラ (sparkling). A third category, gijougo (擬情語), specifically describes emotions: ワクワク (excited), ドキドキ (heart pounding).` },
];

